, and Messianic anticipations lead to new forms of religious and political law? What styles of universality were implied by the abject state of the pure creature, at sea in a creation abandoned by its creator? And how did circumcision operate as both a marker of ethnicity and a means of conversion and civic naturalization? Written with clarity and grace, Citizen-Saints will be of enormous interest to students of English literature, religion, and early modern culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aChristian drama, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aChristian saints in literature. 0aCitizenship in literature. 0aPolitical plays, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitical theologyxHistory of doctrinesy16th century. 0aPolitical theologyxHistory of doctrinesy17th century. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  ashakespeare, citizen saint, antigone, paul, barabbas, othello, caliban, isabella, samson, death, martyrdom, politics, theology, religion, citizenship, state of emergency, sovereignty, sovereign, ruler, law, messiah, circumcision, judaism, assimilation, difference, race, conversion, naturalization, doctrine, saints, literature, british, classics, renaissance, jew, malta, marlowe, fellowship, belonging, tempest, creature, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226157443423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226157443/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles